{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Average device characterization data are summarized in Extended Data Tables 1 and 2.",
    "Unencoded magic-state data were collected over a single 24-h period on ibm_peekskill v.2.5.4 on all physical pairs and the best-performing edge is reported in Extended Data Table 2.",
    "Although the unencoded magic-state data were not interleaved with encoded-state tomography, the best-performing pair of physical qubits was found to have a low two-qubit error per gate of 0.38%, and this error is comparable with the lowest two-qubit error per gate for edges used in the encoded magic-state experiments.",
    "Real-time feedforward control of qubitsIn the past decade, several experiments were performed that exploit fast feedback or real-time control within the execution of a quantum program.",
    "Fast feedback has been used for conditional reset [63][64][65][66], state and gate teleportation [67][68][69] with low branching complexity and in more demanding algorithms such as the iterative-phase estimation protocol 70, to name a few."
  ],
